A new World Bank report shows that although the commodity outlook has improved in general, South Africa's raw materials are not highly sought-after while unemployment remains high and the country remains one of the most inequal societies in the world. The Bank has revised the country's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) upwards.

It expects GDP to grow slowly at 1.4% in 2018 and to 1.8%in 2019, reaching almost 2% in 2020. The South African Reserve Bank leading business cycle indicators rose in the last quarter of 2017, supporting the case for further improvement. 

The bank says higher potential growth will require ambitious structural reforms. Amina Accram reports… --SABC--